*div p {
//styling
}
targets p tag inside the div, but it will target all the p tags inside div including any <p> tag which is under any other
element, like <p> inside any <li> tag which is inside the div
<div>
	<p>styling applied to me</p>
	<ul>
		<li><p>styling will be applied for this as well</p></li>
	</ul>
</div>
if we don't want that, we just want to target <p> which is/are directly under <div>, we can achieve that by
div > p {
//styling
}


*for targetting just next sibling/element
div + p {
	//styling
}
if we want to target <p> which is just after <div>
<div>
	//other stuff
</div>
<p>I will get targetted</p>


*If we want to style something with it's attribute, like if we want to target all the anchor tag <a> having attribute target
a[target]{
	//styling
}
to target any attribute with specific value
a[target='_blank']{
	//styling will be applied to all the anchor tag having target value as _blank
}


*CSS Grid provides 2-D grid layout to dom, it is similar to flexbox but more powerful, we can use align-items & justify-content
just as we use in flexbox.

display: grid; //creates grid
All direct child items are grid items

difference between flex and grid layout is that flex is not capable of 2D layouts, either it can set along a row or a column
with grid we can have 2D layouts
Its good to use grid for the outer layout of whole page

whatever style we will apply to grid will obviously affect our grid-items and that would be our requirement as well

<div class="parent">
	<div></div>
</div>

.parent{
	display: grid; //this alone will not do anything unline flex which moves the direct elements to one line
	grid-template-columns: 200px 200px 200px; //this will align direct child elements in three columns of 200px, if we will
											  //if we will have more than 3 direct child elements then they will go to next row
											  //and if we will have less than 3 columns then remaining columns will remain
											  //empty
	grid-template-columns: 200px auto 200px; //this will cover whole row making first and 3rd column of 200px width and middle
											 //column will take rest of the space of the window
	grid-template-columns: auto auto auto; or repeat(3, auto); //will give equal width to all the three rows and will cover
															   //complete row
	grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr; //we generally use size in grid in fractions(fr), this will also cover whole row making
										//second column of double the size of 1st and 3rd
	grid-gap: 1rem; //to give margin space around grid items(top, bottom, right, left)
}
											
Rows:
.parent{
	display: grid;
	grid-template-rows: 1fr 2fr 3fr; //this will set direct children of the parent element, 1st element to particular default
									 //height second to it's double height, third it's triple height, if there will be more
									 //direct elements then they will be in their default height
	grid-auto-rows: 3fr; //this will set all the remaining child elements to three times of the default size
}


*For 2D, we will have to use both columns and rows
.parent{
	display: grid;
	grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
	grid-template-rows: 1fr 2fr 3fr;
	grid-auto-rows: 3fr;
}
//this will create 2 columns of equal width covering whole width of the browser window, will give 1 times width to the first row
//2times to second row, three times to the third row, if there will be more than 6 items then they will get 3times height bcz of
//grid-auto-rows: 3fr


*If we don't want a regular, consistant layout but we want one item with our desirable column and row span
we can apply styling to that particular item by targetting it, other items will be set according to our regular layout

.particular-child-item{
	grid-column-start: 1;
	grid-column-end: 4; //this will start that item from first column and will take it till 4th column
	grid-row-start: 1;
	grid-row-end: 3; //this will start the item from first row and will take the item till 2nd row
}
it consider lines from the layout start, if we keep 4 as column end that 4 will be 4th line column wise, which will be starting
of 4th column
it will consider lines of our set regular layout


*In order to make it responsive or setting minimum and maximum columns width/row height
.parent{
	display: grid;
	grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
}
this will not set the number of columns (bcz of auto-fit) but will set the minimum(300px here) and maximum (1fr here)
where ever it will see that window width is decreasing then it will send items to next row, keeping atleast 300px width of the
items, if window size is enough then it will set equal width of all the items

it is good for some usecases like image galary but not good for many usecases as no one would want 3 items in one row and 2 
items in another


*if we want to set our layout more easily, we can do that with grid-template-areas
.parent{
	display: grid;
	grid-template-areas:
		'h h h'
		'c c s'
		'b1 b2 b3'
		'f f f';
}

.header {
	grid-area: h; 
}
similarly we can point our keyword same as mentioned in grid-template-areas with the classes of the direct child elements like
content, sidebar, boxes, footer
it makes easy to plan out grid layout.

We can use media queries with grid layout as well, redefining our layouts, column widths in media queries according to the 
requirement.


*SASS(Syntactically Awesome StyleSheets) is CSS preprocessor/precompiler which enhances the functionality of CSS, other
preprocessors include Less, Stylus etc. It allows CSS to work like a programming language, cut down repeated code etc.

It uses .scss(preferred) or .sass file extensions, browser doesn't read SASS file as it reads .css file by adding link to the 
html file, it must be compiled down to regular css and then browser reads it 
